<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Foil Stamping" class="currentChild" href="Foil_Stamping">Foil Stamping</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In <a title="Binding and Finishing" href="Binding_and_Finishing">binding and finishing</a>, a finishing operation in which a design or other image is pressed onto a <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a>. In foil stamping, a heated <a title="Die" href="Die">die</a> containing a <a title="Relief" href="Relief">relief</a> (raised) image presses down on a roll of foil passing above the <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a> to be decorated. As the die hits the foil, it is transferred to the substrate. Many paperback books, hardcover book <a title="Jacket" href="Jacket">jacket</a>s, and various types of packaging are foil stamped. Foil is available in many different colors, patterns, finishes, textures, etc. Foil stamping replaced an earlier process known as <a title="Bronzing" href="Bronzing">bronzing</a>. Foil stamping that occurs in tandem with <a title="Embossing" href="Embossing">embossing</a> is known as <a title="Foil Embossing" href="Foil_Embossing">foil embossing</a>. 
</p>
<p id="l3">
See also <a title="Die" href="Die">Die</a> and <a title="Binding and Finishing" href="Binding_and_Finishing">Binding and Finishing</a>. 
</p>
